[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:743.J.T973.KJ652 AJT62.A62.QJ.T87 Q98.T7.K8652.Q93 K5.KQ98543.A4.A4"]
[VersionToken "6d91857b7e8060b1bff521bff69e89039428dd58b8ee133d51320916c84d192e"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
Pass 1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4NT Pass 5H =1= Pass 5NT =2= Pass 6H =3= Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:2 keycards, no trump Q"]
[Note "2:king ask"]
[Note "3:no kings lower than hearts"]
{North opens 1\S.  What do you respond with? 
You have a powerhouse, plenty strong enough to jump-shift. But playing 2/1 it's usually simpler when you make the 2/1 response, and save your jumping for later - if at all. So just bid 2\H, knowing North must keep the bidding open.
North responds 3\h, setting the trump suit.   
Now you are definitely  interested in slam.  Since you have controls in all the side suits, you go right to keycard Blackwood, using the 1430 system.  Partner responds 5\H.   

Partner's 5\H shows two keycards without the trump queen.  But we have the other 3 keycards, and the trump queen.  If partner has the two minor kings we might have a grand.  We ask about these with our 5NT bid.  Unfortunately, partner responds 6\H (playing specific kings, this denies any kings lower than hearts).  We will pass and play there.
This is a good slam, cold if West makes any opening lead other than a \C. With a \C lead, South will have to pull trumps and play to discard a loser on the \ST.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "W:A.AQJ753.742.KJ4 T874.62.JT.AT962 QJ2.KT.KQ865.Q87 K9653.984.A93.53"]
[VersionToken "1e6a2e4e6a0e33269be943adb36876d7ab229503b8d9f5deb8d691ad537ad74b"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1H Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{How do you start this action? [Bid 1H]
You open 1\H and partner responds 2\D.  What do you rebid? 
Partner's 2 over 1 bid sets up a game force.
You have a good-looking hand, but you need to find a trump suit before showing extra strength, so she bids just 2\H.  You are in a game forcing auction, so partner won't pass you.
Partner now jumps to 4\h.  What do you do now? 

Partner's jump to 4\h is Fast Arrival - showing a minimum game forcing hand.  Even though we have extra values, this won't be enough for slam opposite 13 or so points.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "S:AQ862.T4.K65.K87 K97543.A6.Q97.J6 J.KQJ753.432.Q54 T.982.AJT8.AT932"]
[VersionToken "78f1cb2c0bbf3d942cd2340065ef342decf2e53beec255a6a4235c3bb38b88a4"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\S.  
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\H in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So we use the forcing 1NT.  South rebids 2\c.   This only promises 3 clubs, so is really just there so we can better describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? 

Now we can bid 2H, and it shows 6+\hs and only 6-10 points. 
South was forced to reply to 1NT, but he is not forced to bid again. With his minimum hand and a tolerance for partner's suit he just passes and the partnership ends up in a reasonable contract.
This hand demonstrates one of the benefits of Forcing 1NT. In standard bidding North's first response would be 2\H, and South would have to bid again, probably 2NT. The partnership might go even higher but in any case would probably not reach a good contract.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:AQ862.A4.95.AK87 T93.QT62.QJ74.T2 K.K753.AT32.J954 J754.J98.K86.Q63"]
[VersionToken "29b9c67f7e301c1e228816e7aab0af8c165f0273d6eaff94e25e7288d220071b"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{West opens 1\S. What should you bid? 
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\C, (or 2\D), in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So you bid 1NT, showing 6-12 points.
West rebids 2\c.  Again, this doesn't promise more than 3\c - it's just leaving room for us to describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? 

We know West doesn't have 4 \Hs, so we show our above-minimum hand by bidding 2NT.
West has extra values and raises to 3NT.
West is happy to play Notrump. He assumes we must have something useful in \Ds and bids 3NT.
3NT seems to be a good contract. There are 8 top tricks and possibilities for a ninth winner in either \Ss, \Ds, or, (the best chance), \Cs.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:862.AQJ753.95.A2 JT43.92.AJ87.Q87 K95.T6.KT32.JT54 AQ7.K84.Q64.K963"]
[VersionToken "a3dd90bc9142c0c9bd27c3243cd125849adc1bf7d4e46e86ca03e1169a0b28ac"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1H Pass 1NT Pass 2H Pass Pass Pass
{North opens 1\H. What should we bid? 
We respond 1NT, just as in standard bidding. The difference is that in this case the 1NT response is forcing on North.
North rebids \hs, promising at least a 6-card suit.  

You have nothing to say over 2\H except pass.
Notice that this is the same bidding and same final contract that would have been reached with standard bidding. Using 2/1 is often like that.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "6"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "W:AQT95.T96.KT86.A 73.KQJ.J3.KT8643 KJ2.874.AQ975.Q2 864.A532.42.J975"]
[VersionToken "54a161c38ba8a5c4ab36c2554eac3be3c7f137d68ce7a6302f7ddb91219e1027"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "W"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 3D Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{How do you open the bidding? 
You open 1\S. East responds 2\D, a natural 2/1 force to game.  What do you rebid? 

You cannot rebid your \ss, but you have have decent support for partner's \ds, so raise to 3\d.  You are in a game forcing auction so it won't end there.
East always intended to play a \S contract. He now bids 4\S, using Fast Arrival to indicate he has no slam aspirations.
4\S is cold, and if the defenders don't take their \H tricks immediately you will make an overtrick.}

